At this point, I said," you need to take it down a couple notches."  We asked to speak to the manager and he said, "I'll get the manager in 3 minutes when we open." Weekend dinner..  We were eagerly anticipating dining  in this establishment after the glowing  reviews from reputable food critics/periodicals and even the esteemed Michelin guide no less! Our experience though mirrored though the same sentiments of dismal service as voiced out  by multiple diners. The critics either live in a parallel universe or had preferential service as evidenced by their glowing reviews.  PROS: food B+- pork belly was succulent and tasty lump crab with green curry was bracingly spicy the whole branzino was tangy and tasty --food prices were reasonable for the area  nice location- cavernous tastefully decorated, rustic with Asian accents  CONS: food: - the wings were extra crispy but tasted like cardboard with a side of bland ketchup - the chicken inasal was tough and dry ( ordered 2 but only 1 arrived but charged us for 2!!) - the ribeye was unseasoned and parts of it were raw ( had to be returned and replaced)..they did not bother to ask for our temperature preference - 2 lumpia- crispy but the vinegar sauce was not appropriate for the meat filling ( arrived after the main course...in time for dessert) - plain rice --served in cardboard paper bowls? - garlic rice- bland..garlic sprinkled after it was fried?  dessert: authentic Asian?--chocolate chip cookie and ice cream!  Service: Dismal and pitiful.. - they sat 3 of us in a 6 person table - 20 mins. before our server even came to us ( I had to flag someone else down) - table was still filthy  when we were seated( food scraps with water stains from previous customer)..the apologetic server cleaned it up upon our request! - we asked for a spoon 3x from 3 different servers..never arrived - 2 drinks ordered at the same time ( glass of wine ) arrived 10 mins. apart -overall: service was slow, uncoordinated, inattentive and non existent except for everyones apologies for being understaffed..  THE KICKER: The chef and owner? was actually seated close to us dining outside with VIP guests and oblivious to the surrounding chaos? If he could not notice his crew scampering around like cockroaches in daylight then he should just open a food truck. The table next ours complaining of poor/slow service  ,the lines in the unattended entry way building up ..which was actually next to his table. Thats because the host had to pitch in , bus tables and serve dishes leaving disgruntled potential guest  outside to leave for other establishments. The chef being the captain of this slow sinking ship should re learn business management 101 to somehow make Kaliwa ( meaning left in Filipino) make a U-turn to  back to respectability.

Tried Kaliwa for dinner during first phase of pandemic reopening. Restaurant is practicing distancing, servers are wearing masks, and using single use cups and utensils. Food was fresh, hot, and delicious,  and the drinks were strong and tasty. Being able to sit on the wharf with a view of the water was welcome after 3 months indoors. I have never ordered so much takeout and it has allowed me to try places that I've always wanted to before COVID-19. Kaliwa was high on my list and it did not disappoint.  I ordered the Red Curry with Blue Crab and Crispy Garlic, Panang Curry, and a side of fries. I know, fries is a weird addition but I love fries, it was on the menu so I just went with it.  I ordered for pickup and the food was all packed in cardboard containers. I still can't figure out if these are recyclable or not. They are lined with wax or plastic. I use picking up food as a nice excuse to get out and walk to other neighborhoods so my walk home was about 25 min. The containers held up! No leaks!  The dishes, when I got home, were very unattractive. I'm adding photos but they really don't do them any justice. Don't worry, because the flavors are incredible!  The Red Curry with Blue Crab is phenomenal. You get so much crab! It's the type of dish I didn't want to end so I just ate small portions to savor the taste.  The Panang Curry was not what I expected. This is usually my favorite Thai dish, but Kaliwa's take is more of a savory curry with charred pork belly, onions, and whole peanuts. I prefer a panang curry that is creamier, sweeter, with tofu or chicken, chopped peanuts, and broccoli or carrots. It still tasted great, just not what I was hoping for.  Now, the fries... I have no idea why I got fries but the serving is huge and I really enjoyed them with my curry!

Well... I wasn't going to write a review but I have never had such high expecttions for a place be ruined by unnecesary hassle and illegal activity. Don't get me wrong, the food I had at this place was very good but it seemed just about everything about the service went wrong. I am writing this after calling the management to report that an extra $10 had been charged to my card without my authorization. Although it is over now and completely resolved this whole experience just rubbed me the wrong way and I want to warn others so they don't have to go through the same. I came in at 3 on a Friday afternoon. It was not busy at all. Our first server was very nice, attentive and answered our questions. My friend and I were just about ready to order when instead of our server coming another server came to take our order. Her service was average and she seemed to be doing the minimum. I ordered the oxtail and my friend ordered the pork belly with onions. The oxtail was flavourful and the rice porrige with it was nicely seasoned. The Korean pork belly was also flavourful and we ate all the food. The service was quick but as we finished the meal the server made she made a strage comment about us finishing the food. She acted surprised that we finished all the food and said that people didn't always like it. It seemed really weird to me and kind of unprofessional for her to bad mouth her own restaurant's food. I'm kind of an all or nothing person when it comes to tips and since I didn't really like how the restaurant switched our servers halfway through the meal or the service of the second sever I decided not to tip because I knew it would go to her. My friend decided to do the same. We walked out of the restaurant with a generally good experience and decided to enjoy the rest of our day at the Wharf. This is where it gets bad. Three days later a charge shows up on my statement. I was initially charged for the meal but that charge has now disappeared and has been replaced with a charge from Kaliwa for $10 more than my meal. I call them immediately they write down my info but it's New Years, they say they'll look into it and get back to me on the 2nd or 3rd. It's the 4th, no calls. I call them and I give them and tell the person I'm talking to that I've already voiced my issue and my info has already been recorded. He basically confirms that no one has looked into it at all. He takes care of it, finds my order and tells me that I was right, my meal was $10 less than what I was charged for and says he'll contact the accounting department and refund me the $10. Issue has been cleared up, this whole phone call took about 30 minutes. The guy I talked to was  but I still felt like I was being blamed a little too much for not leaving a tip. After all me not leaving a tip gives the server absolutely no right to illegally add $10 onto my bill. The employee I was on the phone with says the server switch might have been due to change of shifts but I knew that wasn't true because I saw my previous server waiting on other tables as I walked out the door. THIRTY MINUTES LATER I get a call from the employee again. He pronounces my name wrong. (He has read it multiple times at this point.) He askes me if I have checked my email yet for the message about the $10 refund. It has literally been 30 minutes. I do not check my email that often. I just want to move on, leave the past in the past and not go back to restaurants that try to scam me but I check my email, and confirm I got it. 8 DAYS LATER my mess with this restaurant is finally over. I don't have my refund yet but I really hope at least that will show up as it is supposed to. I'm just ready to be done dealing with this and I want future diners to know that if you want unauthorised charges on your credit card and want to worry about people stealing your money if you don't tip them, Kaliwa is the place to go! Overhyped.  Overpriced.  Our first time at Kaliwa so our group has been building anticipation and excitement until our actual reservation date.  The location was right smack in a very busy social hub so we understood all the distractions outside and inside...it really felt like a busy thoroughfare inside the restaurant.  There seemed to be too many servers coming and going the whole time we were there.  Unfortunately, having more than enough staff did not make the food arrive in good time.  Our birthday celebrant had to wait more than 30 minutes for his entrée -- we were all done with our food and his was just getting delivered!  That was really bad.  And the Michelin-Bib-Gourmand-acknowledged menu really did look impressive...ON PAPER.  The actual servings (except for the flounder, at least it was a whole fish) left us totally dissatisfied and disenchanted.  When the sizzling Sisig arrived in a small skillet, we actually thought it was a mistake...that some other table ordered Sisig as an "appetizer."  Realizing it was the entrée one of us ordered floored us!  Then came the Bibimbap.  Sigh.  I (this reviewer) actually ordered it.  I've had Bibimbap before.  There was a full cup of rice underneath an egg done 'sunny side up,' with approximately a tablespoon each of bean sprouts, spinach, kimchi, and maybe two pieces of mushrooms and pickled cucumber.  I went ballistic internally!  I have made Bibimbap myself.  And elsewhere, Bibimbap would come served with some Bulgogi-type meat strips.  I didn't read the menu well enough to realize it didn't mention the inclusion of any meat.  Still...  Despite the missing ingredient, this bowl of Bibimbap was so bland on its own.  Believe me, I've had Bibimbap that proved tasteful even without the Gochujang (red bean paste)!  Sigh.  I could go to HMart (Korean grocery) and eat Bibimbap from their food court and be truly happy with the quality I'll get, nevermind the ambiance!  Tsk.  Tsk.  Tsk.  It got worse when the order for Foie Grass Dumplings ("Pancit Molo") was served to another person in our group.  Four little round dumplings with bits of spring onions and ginger(?) slices, and about a cup of tasteless broth...it just wasn't "entrée-worthy."  The other food we ordered were also so-so.  They might've been better than the aforementioned dishes, but they weren't what we expected.  Michelin or no Michelin, having to pay more than the usual for the same food that we could find in other (under-hyped) restaurants really hurt our feelings.  We would've loved to lift up Kaliwa and put it on a culinary pedestal...but, sadly...  To anyone who's gotten this far in this review, may I suggest that you try (if you haven't yet) PURPLE PATCH's Sizzling Sisig.  (Their portion is good enough for two, and there's not a lot of fat in the meat.) Find out why our group was suddenly disenchanted with Kaliwa.  Purple Patch is in the Mt. Pleasant area, it's another restaurant that offers modernized Filipino dishes.  Location may generate some fancy hype, but really good, tasteful food (especially those served generously) is what makes customers return (repeatedly).  Lastly...the biggest disappointment for our group..."we took it (Halo-Halo) off our menu."  Why, oh why???  Kaliwa's current desserts weren't even uniquely special.  We honestly all said that we wouldn't be going back to Kaliwa (unless somebody else were paying for their pricey meal...LOL).
fancy new style Asian food ! Great! Super !
Service was great and the green curry so GOOD!!! My friend got the blue crab red curry and that was excellent as well!

Kaliwa  is an asian restaurant that has 3 cuisines: Philippines, Korea and Thai.  Each cuisine is limited to I think what is best on their respective origins but they have limited selections on their menu which I think is good as customers are faced with 3 different cuisines and might be overwhelmed by it.  Parking - this is the wharf ao parking can be a challenge and expensive too.  Ambiance - i can barely tell that this is an asian restaurant. The interiors are like mashups of modern and european touch and trying hard to infuse an asian ambiance.  The chandeliers can be easily mistaken as those tiny sea shells but it turns out it is a wooden balls.  Cozy? Maybe on the yes side.  Noise level is too high, i can hear people talking loudly because they need as the sounds coming from the sound system plus other people talking.  Food  Kinilaw - All Filipinos love Kinilaw. Each province in the Philippines have different variations but one thing should be in common, vinegary-taste with strong hint of giner and lime and i think even the inexperienced or aspiring Filipino cook would’ve gotten this easily but ssdly, Kaliwa didn’t get this.  Kare-kare  At first glance, it looks pale compared to outlr usual kare-kare. Maybe because of the peanut that they use for the sauce.  The sauce in the kare-kare is creamy. I like the creaminess of the sauce but there is something missing  that i acn’t put my finger on it but i like it in general. Tip: ask them to grind the peanuts that they put as a topping it will be more infuse more flavor to the sauce.  All in all, their take on one of the greatest Filipino dish is a little apot on. The portion is enough for one serving.  The beef perfectly blends with the sauce and vegetables.  Price wise, comparing the ratio serving vs the price, it’s expensive for me.

Portion was extremely small but love the dish. Not sure about the sauce, but it was light and tasty. The blue crab curry was one of the best. Would be perfect if it was a tad more spicy. The kaeng daeng was the least favorites...the coconut flavor was too overpowering. For desserts, u need to try the pandan cake with coconut ice cream. Ambiance was a 5 but the off white seat covering needs to be washed or replaced. Hard to recouncile a high end restaurant with nasty cloth seat cover!!!

Wonderful wood oven-fired cooking. Sit at the bar to watch them prepare your food. Ironically, good luck getting a drink there, though - the bartender won't  keep an eye on you so you have to either crane your neck around for a while, searching to make eye contact with someone who works there, or, bug one of those already busy chefs (not ideal for either of you). Great food, though.
The food was superb and the service was some of the best I've had at a restaurant.

Had a great experience here. Ended up stopping for lunch and was completely impressed. It is a little pricey as it is justified, but it would definitely be a place I would go again for a special ocassion.
Great environment, food and staff!!

For those taking a stroll along the wharf or for those who dont want to wait in line at this busy restaurant, DO NOT order the beef bulgogi and rice outside in the stand that they run outside. The meat is as tough as leather. This place would be liable for someone choking on their meat. Sure the dish is only $6 but my spouse and I wanted a quick to go box to bring to our hotel at Hyatt House. What a disappointment. Get better quality meat and charge a little more.

I had really high hopes for this place. Unfortunately, it was just ok. The lumpia had a thick wrapper unlike authentic lumpia, which has a paper thin crispy wrapping. Sisig was fine but not great. I did really like my drink and the atmosphere.
Great Asian street food on the outside of the main restaurant.  In case you have a dog or little kids, this is perfect instead of sitting inside.  Try the burger, very good

We dropped in for a quick cocktail, a refreshing Mekong Mule, and Torrance suggested their Lumpiang Shaghai for an accompaniment. The crispy shrimp and pork fried rolls hit the spot. Kaliwa is nicely decorated restaurant, featuring south east Asian fare. I intend to revisit for a sit down meal.
Mixology drinks are off the charts here. The chef will accommodate celiacs.

We waited 30 MINUTES to order when there were only 4 people in front of us. The person behind the counter was moving so slowly. Then, they ran out of almost every item on the menu right before we were about to order. Honestly unacceptable.
The wait is absolutely horrendous. There were two people behind the counter, and only one of them working at the SLOWEST pace I’ve ever seen. I don’t understand how they’ve stayed open this long.

Food is good, service is ridiculously slow; at least the three times we've been. The server stopped by and asked if he could clear a few things, then took the drink menu but none of the finished dishes or glasses

I had the pleasure of eating dinner at Kaliwa recently, and I was very pleasantly surprised.  I enjoy the Wharf area, and have visited it a number of times, but for some reason I hadn't ever come across this particular restaurant.  When I visited it was for a late dinner on a weeknight (Wednesday), and my date and I were able to be seated quickly even without a reservation which was nice.  The decor in the space is very appealing, and our servers were polite and checked in on us often, even though it was pretty busy.  Most importantly, the food was delicious! I ordered three dishes and my date ordered two, which was plenty, and I especially enjoyed the Panang Curry. It was phenomenal! The Bibimbap was excellent as well.  Lastly, to touch on something others have mentioned, it is a bit expensive, however so are the majority of the restaurants at the wharf; just keep in mind when you're perusing the menu that you'll likely want to order two or three dishes.  I'll definitely visit again! If you're on the fence, you won't regret giving it a shot.
Was expecting so much more based on the menu but food was just OK. If someone wanted to go here for dinner I would go again but I would not suggest it to them as a place to go.

I organized a social event on March 31 for a large group of visitors to the DC area as part of the National Cherry Blossom Festival, and arranged to have it at Kaliwa. Nikki, the general manager, was wonderful to work with, and was very responsive & collaborative for the event planning. We had a private space up on the mezzanine level and were served buffet style, which worked out well. The one hiccup that occurred was encountering several additional guests arriving unannounced, but it was not a problem b/c the chef and Nikki were able to seamlessly provide more tasty food and servers on very short notice to​ meet our needs.  The food has great flavor with wonderful vegetarian options.  There's a nice selection of beer, wine, and unique cocktails.  Kaliwa's staff helped make the evening a great success! I highly recommend Kaliwa for anyone planning to host a social event at the District Wharf.

The food here is amazing. The roast chicken might be the best I've had. The service was lacking, however. We sat at a table in the bar area for lunch and our server was tending to our table, 10 or so people seated at the bar and a large table of 14. He was working very hard but we waited for him to come by our table for 30 minutes at one point. Given the prices they are charging, management needs to staff this place appropriately.
Great location, mouth watering food, and the service was top tier. Anticipated needs before we even expressed them. Impressive wine list (sommelier Nikki was very helpful).

Kaliwa is beautiful in a great location and offers good food, a total novelty for a filipino restaurant but is well overpriced. There are dozens of places next to it that I would rather visit. A group of 4 can easily consume well over $300 for a meal my Filipino coworkers can easily prepare. It's a good to try kind of restaurant but they won't find me there for the second time.
For true experience, the Chef's Progressive menu (for four) at Kaliwa was the best I've personally experienced in DC or elsewhere in the US. Fantastic culinary journey!
Great beef cheeks in fermented shrimp!
Good food I love the lechon kawali
Filipino, korean and Thai dishes done very well in a beautiful space ! One of the few restaurants in my heavy rotation!

The Host was friendly and the server was very attentive.  Very cultured restaurant. The food taste great very fresh and well seasoned.  Not your traditional Asian food. Do not have expectations of Panda Express type of Asian food. You've been warned.Alot things on the menu I was not able to identify with but it was very good.

I generally make better Asian dishes at home and I have no particular experience with Asian cooking. The flavors were unimaginative and one dish was so salty it was inedible. You are much better going to any authentic restaurant for an Asian meal. The service was good although they did forget one of the dishes we ordered. It was like if Guy Fieri opened a generic Asian fusion restaurant on a whim. Or on a dare.

While this place looked nice and most of the food was pretty tasty.... this place is so ridiculously over priced for the portions size. I thought they had delivered something to us by mistake because it seemed like a appetizer. Especially after they emphasized that this food was ment to be shared. You only managed to really get two spoonfuls of food between two people. Also our Adobe was overly salty and lacked traditional flavors. If you want Filipino, Korean, or thai food, there are so many other options out their that wont put you at $128 for 2 drinks 1 app and 2 entrees.
Phenomenal!!  A bit pricey, but very worth the price. Great staff and service. Phenomenal food and drinks. Great atmosphere!b

Good flavor...but this is not Filipino street food. Food took too long. Too over priced for too little. Need to put more in their menu. If you’re looking to get street food experience, you’re outta luck here.
Good stuff! The halo halo was pretty good
The Korean wings and blue crab curry. DELICIOUS! And fantastic service
Really great food! I'm Filipino and Kare Kare's one of my favorite dish and I thought they made theirs spot on! So good!
Very horrible experience,  horrible  food, overpriced and they took more than 1 hour after getting an order. Never go there for Lunch, not to mention $17 to park. I would give no star if I can

Fantastic food with a distinctive flavor profile. Had a great birthday dinner with the fam. Family style dining with shared plates and they have a bowl of rice per person along with the dishes ordered. The flounder was hands down the best I've ever had, delicious with a burst of unique Thai flavors. Cocktail menu was certainly interesting and I went with the Lasing (soju & lychee) which did not disappoint! Short ribs were melt in your mouth deliciousness I would definitely order over and over again. We also opted for the lamb stew and Bibimbap, they were nothing special but the remaining dishes more than made up for it. Deducted a star as the hostess neglected to mention the birthday to our server and we did not get a birthday special of any sort. But will definitely go back for the food nonetheless!

Absolutely WORST food I have EVER had at a restaurant. DO NOT GO HERE!!! My family and I spend a lot of time dining in DC and at the wharf, we were excited to try something new and this was horrible. We had a party of 8 and we all left our food 1/2 eaten and couldn’t finish because the food & taste was so bad. The service also wasn’t very good- we came for brunch and I came in with a coffee I had picked up to go. They asked me to toss my coffee which I was totally fine with- but then didn’t have coffee to serve. We all left with tummy aches and a bad taste in our mouth! YUCK! I can’t express enough how bad this food is!

We're having trouble wrapping our heads around this place where there's no room for cliches, conventions, or comfort zones. It's a beautifully decorated, wide-open space, and the artwork is worthy of your attention. Our server was top-notch and seemed to know everything about the menu, even if much of it was unfamiliar to us and could not exactly be explained. But all of it is good quality and worth trying - lots of colors and textures and flavors, but nothing obnoxiously over-the-top. While we thought the Korean-style seafood medley on egg noodles was unremarkable, the blue crab curry was wonderful, with generous chunks of meat and just the right amount of heat. It's a bit pricey, but we enjoyed being thrown for a loop here.
Amazing, a must visit. Some amazing flavors. For a great show sit at the kitchen counter and watch some hard working chefs.

My group had an awesome experience at Kaliwa.  The staff at Kaliwa helped me arrange a reservation for a party of 10, and they allowed us to reserve the table completely for free. Our server was terrific and he offered to split the check 10 ways, which was beyond what we were expecting. A few members of our group arrived late as well, and even though another party had the big table reserved right after us, nobody rushed us through our dinner.  The food was also great. All around terrific experience, and we'll definitely be back!

PARKING ALERT! there is limited public parking in the area so plan ahead, better yet use a ride-share service and avoid the headache of trying to find parking. BTW: the food is amazing! Try the Korean BBQ you won't regret it, especially if you like GA Galbi (Korean BBQ Short Ribs)

Asian cuisine of Philippine, Korea, and Thailand located in very busy and almost impossible to find a parking spot nearby. Food are not authentic and somewhat americanized but still palatable in a nice presentation with modern Asian style dishes. We ordered about 10 dishes and appetizers to share by 7. Service was good and attentive. Service charges for 7 people in our group was automatically charged 20% so be careful when you receive final bill to sign for your credit card charges.

Loved it.  The mussel and clam app was amazing.  You just want to drink the sauce they are swimming in.  The cashew cake was also a major stand out.  New flavor profile for me and super good.  I will be back to taste more of the menu.

i loved their appetizers more than their main dishes. i loved the wings and and the papaya salad. the green curry was a different take on the traditional dish is. the staff was helpful but not sure if it was because they were desperate for business due to shutdown or they are in general nice. i would return.

I visited Kaliwa for the first time for a company event and was extremely satisfied with the entire evening. The atmosphere is clean but not sterile, it maintains a homey and vibrant feel while being immaculately clean. The layout is open and has a lovely 2nd level. I was able to peek up at the screens at the bar between conversation to see who was winning the UFC fights, which I was ecstatic to find they were showing.  I did not order my own food, as this was a planned event, however, I tried every single item and absolutely loved it. I'm a huge fan of seafood and meat and the selections I got to choose from were exquisite. I'm not big on fish but the rockfish they served had me coming back for more. I never waited long for anything at the bar or my table, even though, the place was packed with my coworkers. My glass was always full and so was my stomach by the end. All of the staff were professional and helpful. My wife and I were so impressed that, even though we live over an hour away, will definitely be coming back. We are also recommending Kaliwa to all of our friends and family. What a gem of a place. Thanks, Kaliwa and Muki for making it a such a pleasant and memorable evening.

Last Friday I had friends Judy and Stewart Combo decide to go for dinner.  I asked if they wanted to be adventurous, Stewart said you pick.  I decided to visit Kaliwa after being with Cathal at a Walter Reed benefit for the veterans.  I explained the fare and that we would simply leave it in the capable hands of Cathal and Meshelle.  Interesting concept as we normally go to  a steak or seafood (American style) restaurant.  Loved the decor and warm welcome when we entered (first timers).  We were seated with a view of the open kitchen and main floor.  Courtney our server was fantastic and although not familiar with most of the menu, explained the 4 course menu with great clarity.  We ordered drinks and sat looking at the menu with much discussion.  When she came back and we informed her we were going with the 4 courses, she said simply relax, sit back and enjoy as Chef would create the dining experience.  The short version is that it was the most fantastic selection, pairing and assortment of flavors, spices and seafood/meats my friends had experienced in the Greater Washington DC area.  So much so that Stewart began photo bombing and posting during the entire meal.  I could go on and on but the fact of the matter is, it is now a must see and must experience "go to" restaurant for his family and friends.  Congratulations on all points.  My sincere thanks to all of the staff, front and back of house.  Excellence in motion for sure.  Well done Cathal and Meshelle. Tom and Denise Burke
Cool restaurant. Good food.. Bold flavors.
Food was gross and over salted.
Everything here has pork in it and they charge by the can for refills.

I went during their happy hr on a saturday and their food was amazing! Its like $5-$7 for little dishes, so you can try a few things on the menu without going broke. We got the spring rolls, ginger fried rice, pork skewers (careful they are a little spicy!), and oysters! The food came out pretty fast and the atmosphere is really chill
We had an amazing experience at Kaliwa. The staff was incredible and the ambience was elegant. Compliments to Chef Paolo. Thank you!
The pork is so good! And the fish melts in your mouth!
Love the atmosphere and all the Filipino food. Highly recommend!

Finally went to Kaliwa during winter restaurant week. Delicious, asian comfort food with great service and ambience. We enjoyed every bit of our meal. Dishes ordered- Yellowtail, Green papaya salad, Pork belly (Korean)- it was the star of the night. Pork just melted in my mouth and was so flavorful and filling.
A Southeast Asian culinary heaven....Great food and awesome service.

Amazing cuisine! I tried to book a table at the last minute and they were full. That didn't stop us, we still showed up and found some seats at the bar. They were super busy with excellent service from everyone there. Jason greeted us right away and took our drink order and told us the specials. Very diverse menu. I highly recommend this place. Great beer/drink selection, cozy atmosphere and decor. We met two of the chef's, who you can tell they put their heart into it. We will definitely be back with family and friends.

This place is somewhat overpriced. Like their happy hour menu is quite laughable. But the drinks were ok. The service was not the best. I needed to search for the server for a few items including the check, and he could not speak good English. This resulted in a few awkward exchanges. There are a lot of nice places in this area. The space was gorgeous, but I would find a better alternative close by.

Amazing! Great,  interesting,  fun, exciting food.  GOOD prices for fantastic food at a fantastic location! I was with a large group and we tasted everything.  It was all amazing,  and I am a picky,  fearful eater. I felt like I was always in safe hands,  visiting with family friends
Delicious food!
Great food and outstanding service. Rarely have I had such a positive experience at a restaurant!
Nice mixture of 3 Asian cuisines. Could be a bit cheaper counting that it's small plates format.

one of the worst restaurants i've ever experienced. i went with 4 patrons including myself and we all got our meals 15 minutes after each other. so there was an hour difference between the time the first patron got their dinner and the last patron.  when the food came, it was the weirdest food. didn't look appetizing, didn't taste appetizing. I should have known better because when I entered the restaurant, there’s no smell of tasty or appetizing food.
Great atmosphere, enjoyed the small plates, and food taste phenomenal!

Had an aweful experience. I was served with raw chicken inasal was served. And when I gave it to the food runner they gave back the charred meat That i just gave to them. Food inspection department should look into this. Unsanitary.
Super good food
Come support an awesome team. Really robust flavors to be found here.  I always get the whole fried fish.
Pricey. Newly build resto. Classy ambiance Little choices. Thai flounder is the best but the price is also the best $32...
Excelent food

Nice ambiance and decor. Good service.  Food delivered as it was prepared. We had the Tour for two, chefs selection. Overpriced for an "ok" experience.  Billed for 2 Pineapple juice w/club soda, as if they were cocktails.
The best experience I've had at the wharf. The serving sizes are not too small. Service is spectacular.
Delicious food, great space, wonderful staff, refreshing drinks, an all around incredible sensory experience!
I went there one night and the owner was cooking at the bar and I asked him what should I get and he suggested 3 different items so I got all 3 and they were amazing. I cannot wait to go back!
A tasty blend of three distinct Asian cuisines.  Great intro intro Filipino (thai and Korean) dishes and culture
High quality food, excellent service. Moderate portions.

(Translated by Google) Atmosphere was good, and meal was good, too. Korean, Thai and other dishes are served in a somewhat localized way. underwhelming  not really pinoy

I've been looking forward to coming to Kaliwa so was extremely disappointed to learn that almost everything contained pork. The flounder I wanted and even the green beans were made with pork. We ended up only getting the fried chicken sandwich, which was mostly sandwich bread and was okay. Our waiter was attentive and the service was good.  Would only recommend Kaliwa to those who eat pork.
Great food, but the service was rushed.   We were served our orders so quickly that it felt like we didn't have time to stop and enjoy the food we were eating.
Loved the food. Loved the service. And the fact that there’s a Metro station within walking distance will make it easy to return often.
I have tried many dishes at Kaliwa and have loved them all.  You must try it
Decent but expensive
Awesome food and service, definitely going back.
First time there with friends and we had a great time. The food was spectacular.
We had a large party and they were very accommodating. The food and wine were delicious. Looking forward to going again!
Great food and experience. The vibe is fun. The service is good.
Creative, tasty, and stylish, Kaliwa is your go-to stop for Pan-Asian food and cocktails on the wonderful Wharf!

Wow! If you go in here with no expectations they will blow you away. The food is good, and is delivered to your table as it's ready. Keep that in mind when you dine as a group and it'll be an enjoyable experience. The service was amazing and we couldn't have been happier with the quality. Not traditional in all the best ways.

Great food, nice alcohol selection. Right on the wharf with a lot of space. Had a dish from each country (Philippines, Korea and Thailand) and all were good. Dishes from Thailand are spicy, can recommend the dumplings and pork Filipino dish.  Ignore the bad reviews that say this place is too expensive, it’s appropriately priced for the location and quality.
We had a lunch party here with the family on Sunday. The service was great and the food was very good! worth the price!
Great food, good service, nice environment.

The ambiance was nice until you go to sit-there were so many stains on the seats. Next, the food didn't have much taste of any regions they represented except for the over-powering fish sauce. The only person who enjoyed his dinner was one of the line cooks eating, facing the restaurant, while we waited for ours.
Great food. Interesting food. Really good service. Nice ambience. Even just going to the bar for a drink and an appetizer is a nice experience. Will be back for sure.

The food was very bad. The short ribs were all bones and fat barely any meat on it. Definitely avoid that meal if you’re looking to eat a real meal.  The garlic rice was so greasy it took hours to feel normal.
This is a fun and interesting place.  Upbeat atmosphere and most fascinating foods if one has an appetite to experiment.  The food was great.
Great food and fantastic service! Just make sure to ask your server about spice levels before ordering.
Excellent food and service.
Very urban eastern restaurant by DC water side
Delicious food with great service! Atmosphere was lovely and the wait staff were on point.
great food, atmosphere, service...a LITTLE pricey on some of the items, but nothing that doesn't taste great
Great food, fun place.
Great atmosphere and the food was terrific. We will be back!
Great food and service!

Flexible when we were a little late due to rain and bad commute. Very friendly service. So many great choices for food and drinks. Loved the short ribs, crab curry and spicy pork belly. Every dessert from Chef Josh was a treat for the eyes and mouth. Will be back to try all we missed. Great menu and service!
Fabulous place to explore new flavors, share dishes, and enjoy a relaxing night out. Excellent service, fabulous menu, and lovely atmosphere.

Just a disclaimer, I have Celiac Disease. Immediately after sitting down at the restaurant, the waitress was dismissive when I asked if there was a menu or any markings for items on the menu that were gluten free. She basically said I had about 3 options and that the kitchen would not modify anything to accommodate my allergy. Then I was told that if that was not ok I should just try a different restaurant. So I got up and left. While I do not expect any establishment to bend over backwards for an allergy I was bothered by how much of an inconvenience I seemed. There was nothing on the website to suggest that the options for me would be limited. As a side note, the Irish pub across the walkway was wonderful and had a plethora of options for those with dietary restrictions.

Came here for an anniversary dinner. We were early so headed to the bar for a drink. The scene was so lively watching the chefs and cooks in action we stayed there for our meal. It was a great spot because we got to see the dishes being …

The restaurant is beautiful, the ambiance is wonderful and the food is fantastic! My favorite dish is the blue crab curry thing. I can’t tell you how wonderful that is. Great date night or pre-concert stop!

The food is good but way over priced!  I guess that’s due to the high price rent they pay. Overall great experience the two times I’ve been there but just the price a line makes me give them 4 stars. I could get something similar for way less. Both times I went I spent $200 for two people and I could get the same experience for under $20 lol...
Delicious food,  great selection and very reasonably priced. I will be back!
excellent Filipino and Asian food skillfully presented.  Great waitstaff, very informative.
Food was good, very small portions and you will leave hungry.

This is now our favorite restaurant. Great food and great atmosphere. It's already running like an established restaurant, which shouldn't surprise anyone since it's the folks who ran Restaurant Eve. We'll be back.
Decent food
food was good but size of the portions were so tiny for the price( 2 small pieces of belly for 15$ 😆)

Delicious food with the chef's twist without losing the identity of the traditional flavors. Do mind that it is at the Wharf so prices will reflect as such. If you're not ok with $5 per lumpia, just stick with the entrees.
Amazing experience 👌
Great place for dinner before a show at the anthem! Try the whole fish,  it's really excellent

Great waterfront location. Elegantly designed interior. My friend and I dropped in for a light lunch. We ordered the Korean dumplings for $10. We got four small scantly stuffed dumplings. Sauce was good. We also ordered the pork belly skewers. Two skewers arrived with 2 inches of meat on each. Service was good. Way overpriced and in my view and not very authentic.
Not good for kids.
Great tasting food. Plates are small.

Friendly server, great ambiance but slow and expensive. From the moment you walk in the ambiance are friendly and relax. The host and server super friendly. I wish I can say the same about the food. The food kinda bland and serving are …

The food and drinks were definitely great! And it's definitely worth trying. But I do feel the cleanliness and pricing were an issue.  The table decorations I did not care for and it had food stains on it. My husband's glass was dirty, and the seats have spots on them. I looked at a few other seats around, including the bench and they had spots on them as well.  As far as the pricing, it was difficult to justify. We had the hash, which though it was delicious, was the same price I would expect from a steak. And I can't understand why the green beans would be $9.
Good food. Small portions. It’s really for the vibe.

COME BACK! I know folks had disappointing experiences before, but OMG, I went back last night and it was fantastic! Service was extremely friendly and accommodating and I got to try new Filipino dishes I had never heard of before. Also, save room for the bibinka dessert. Holy moly, it was the best we have ever had and we ended up having two each because they were so good. I wanted a third, but didn't want to look too piggish. Now I regret it and think I might need to go back just for that.
Just ok . Nice restaurant .

Good service. Great food! I had the curry blue crab which was tangy but amazing. I also had the fire grilled chicken, greens beans and fried grouper. The frozen mai tai was strong but delicious! Food served SALO-salo meaning shared.
We gave it a chance, liked the interior but did not like at all the food.  I do not recommend.

Fantastic restaurant with reasonable prices. The Jae Yuk Gui, or spicy pork belly, was fantastic. It was cooked so tender, it literally melted in my mouth. We also had the Jjampong (seafood soup), which had a nice umami flavor but was not too strong. The lumpia and sticky rice was excellent as well. The food came out very quickly too. I love the variety of food, and the execution was pretty great too!
Food - authentic Drinks - Funky Ambiance - gorgeous Service - excellent My family such had a wonderful experience at Kaliwa.  We kept coming back and they are consistent all the time.
Best east Asian restaurant on the Wharf.

My wife and I came to the wharf for a fun night out with the kids. I was amazed to see the beautiful decor of the restaurant, and loved the fun atmosphere. Our waitress Diana was very helpful. All the dishes we ordered were great! I highly recommend the whole flounder or the vegan green curry. For dessert we ordered the Pandan cake, which was a wonderful recommendation by our waitress. Overall the restaurant was very good.

Menu is not as clear as one would assume, but the food was well prepared. Im pinoy so i found the filipino food to be somewhat lacking in selection for my taste. Service was attentive and accommodating.

Nothing special, other than the waterfront location and views.  The service was fair at best, and clearly they were understaffed.  The food was consistent, in that it pretty much all seemed to taste the same.  I
My favorite of all the new dining options at the DC Wharf

I love that the menu is divided into three separate Asian ethnic cuisines, with complementary themes, e.g., pork belly is one ingredient that runs across the Filipino, Korean, and Thai sections. And talking of pork belly:  I love the Filipino street-food take on that meat. I’ve had nearly everything in the Filipino section of the menu and was delighted by the combination of vibrant flavors, most of all in the kinilaw hamachi fish on a hot rock. Outstanding. I also really appreciate that steamed rice is unlimited with every dish. It’s so refreshing not to get nickel and dimed. A great addition to DC cuisine diversity.

Wasn’t impressed. I tried the BBQ skewers and they were very fatty. For the price I would expect little to no fat on the small piece of pork.  My wife tried the Pancit Palabok and she didn’t like it. She’s Filipino so knows how it’s supposed be cooked. This dish was very soupy and only had 3 shrimps.  The sauce should be much thicker than what it was. Again for the price one would expect a little more. I also ordered a local beer in a can for only $7 and it was slightly colder than room temperature. I told our waitress and she came back with a cold beer a good 5 mins later. My guess is that they were just put in the cooler but I can’t be certain.  Nice decor and atmosphere. And the Staff seeed to be friendly.

This restaurant is amazing. It's right at the wharf right off the water. The ambience is great very modern. The menu is great it has options from Filipino, Korean & Thai food. I had the flounder whole fish and it was so great. A little spicy but still had great flavor. The vegetables are also really good, green beans and asparagus.
Wish the gill of the fish was pulled out before the cooking.

The cocktails and food were amazing - we especially loved the lumpia, the whole flounder, lamb stew and the pork belly.  The service was excellent and we enjoyed the festive atmosphere - we will definitely return!

Kaliwa has it all -- great food, wonderful service, great downtown vibe. I loved it from the first moment I walked in. And as a Filipino native, I appreciate their fresh take on traditional dishes. The only bad thing about Kaliwa is how it's so far away from my house! Props to Paolo and JR for their mad skills, and to the Armstrongs for being visionaries.
Great big space with unique decor. Decent wine list. Food smelled amazing, but the couple snacks we got were only ok (fried dumplings and rolls). I'll definitely return to try other menu items though
Food, atmosphere, and service were great.  Definitely coming back, thanks Donnie and Ivan!
Great service and delicious food! And the restaurant is beautiful. Highly recommend!
Great service, fun atmosphere, and the food is creative and extremely flavorful.

What made this place special to me was the fun and friendly staff. The decor is festive. The food was not as "authentic" as I would prefer but WAS tasty. The service was attentive. I will be returning.

I'll start with the salt content; I can't even finish the meal as my tongue hurts. As if twisting lemon in the wound, the small portions are a joke compared to the price point. To be clear, if the food was amazing, the portion size would not be an issue .
